India is @linkedin's fastest growing market, says CEO Ryan Roslansky. Revenue in India is growing at 50% YoY, he adds.

On course to touch a 100 million subscribers in India, which is one of our most important markets and R&D hub. Have 700 engineers in India, developing for India and the world.

CEO Roslansky says, they have no lay-off plans but are freezing hiring across some departments. 

6 years after being acquired by @microsoft, LinkedIn is clocking north of $14 bn in revenue.

If we look back a decade from now, I do believe the @microsoft - LinkedIn deal will go down as one of the best tech deals, says CEO Roslansky. Credits Satya Nadella's vision for ensuring Linkedin continues as a standalone entity. 

On Twitter's new blue tick policy, Roslansky says, that while a valuable healthy #Twitter is good for the world, he will continue to use LinkedIn to share professional knowledge.

He also talks about the 'productivity paranoia' & how a different management skillset is required in the hybrid world. He adds, 'focus needs to be on the output of employees.'

From the #GreatResignation to the #GreatUncertainity, CEO Ryan Roslansky sizes up the trends on LinkedIn, on his first India visit as CEO.

In a significant move the #BCCI today announced that Indian women cricketers will now be paid the same match fees as their male counterparts for international matches across formats.

A woman cricketer will now get a match fee of 15 lakhs for a test match, 6 lakh for a one day international and 3 lakh rupees for an international T20 match- that’s a significant increase compared to what they made before.
However, a match fee is only a small component of a cricketer's take home per year. A look at the annual contracts and we can see the vast pay inequity . A male cricketer in Grade A - the likes of #shikhardhawan, #ashwin #pujara have a contract worth 5 crore per year. On the contrary, a woman cricketer in the same category gets paid 50 lakh - that's about 10% of what a male cricketer in Grade A gets paid. That's not all there is an A+ category for male cricketers which includes the likes of #viratkohli #rohitsharma and #jaspritbumrah - they have a 7 crore per year contract. There is no such category for women cricketers.

I spoke to Harmanpreet Kaur (@imharmanpreet_kaur) , Captain of Indian women's cricket team & Diana Edulji , Administrator BCCI & former captain on the Announcement.

In this exclusive interview, a visibly elated #harmanpreetkaur tells me that she is very happy & welcomes this news. She said “ This is very important for all of us because we have been talking about women equality on match fees and I am sure a lot more will happen in future”. And believes that #BCCI would definitely look into the annual contracts in the future.

Former India Captain, Diana Edulja thinks this is the best time to be a woman in cricket & wishes she could get back into the game! According to her BCCI is taking small but positive steps to improve the cause of women’s cricket & public is responding well post 2017.
IPL is coming up, and if the team can crack the World Cup, will be a big move to market women’s cricket says former India Captain

Post the takeover by Tatas, @airindia.in charts a turnaround plan. Won't be easy but Tatas are committed to providing resources, group bandwidth to restore its status to once being the best airline in the world explains new CEO Campbell Wilson in his first interview. 

In talks with Boeing & Airbus to buy new aircraft from 2024. Expect to increase actual operating fleet from 30 aircraft to 60 in 2023, says CEO Wilson.

The turnaround plan for Air India is currently independent of any possible consolidation with @vistara, we are not holding back any plans, talks with Vistara are 'exploratory'.

Adds turnaround process is like a test match, needs patience, ambition & luck. 

Have put in place new revenue management, distribution systems, he says. Aviation is a challenging business, high ATF cost not helping any airline.

'Air India was the best airline in late 1960s but what we did then won't make us the best airline now,' says CEO Wilson. We have to benchmark against the best & do what it takes to get there, he adds.

In his first interview after taking over, Air India CEO Campbell Wilson charts a new flight path for revival & says tripling the fleet and gaining 30% market share in 5 years are the top priorities.

WHO labelled India as the most depressed country in 2018. India's National Mental Health Survey conducted in 2019 estimated that over 56 million Indians suffered from some form of depression and 38 million Indians suffered from anxiety disorder.
Despite the high prevalence of mental disorders in India, over 80% of Indians do not have access to mental care services.
 
In April 2022, CNBC-TV18 launched a campaign, Mind Matters-- an invitation to well-being, with an aim to highlight the importance of mental health, create awareness and eliminate stigma. Today on the occasion of #WorldMentalHealthDay the key question we are asking is what can companies do to address mental health in the workplace. 
 
I had an interesting conversation with Alok Kshirsagar of Mckinsey, Columnist Aparna Piramal Raje who authored Chemical Khichdi : how i hacked my mental health.
Pramath Raj Sinha Founder & Chairman of Harappa education also the founder and trustee of Ashoka University. Radhika Gupta Managing Director & CEO of Edelweiss Asset Management
 
Columnist & Author Aparna says, the biggest change is that top leadership in India Inc is interested in addressing this issue now. She adds that "Workplaces need to be empathetic the way they were during Covid as we are dealing with a “shadow pandemic”
 
Radhika Gupta believes that in the post Covid world there is a recognition that mental health issues are real issues and organizations need to walk a middle path which is very important & don’t need to be too prescriptive but need to show consideration that people have a life outside workplace
 
According to Alok Kshirsagar 40% of Indian workers say they have burnout, suffer from anxiety or depression . Toxic workplace behavior is the number one reason for people quitting , not compensation, he says. 
 
Pramath Raj Sinha Founder & Trustee of Ashoka University doesn’t think there is a silver bullet to making toxic workplaces better. He says. ‘the top leadership should send out a clear signal that certain types of behavior are unacceptable. If people at the top don’t walk the talk the rest of the organisation doesn’t believe in it'
.
.
.
.

The World Health Organisation recently published its World Mental Health Report, 20 years after its landmark 2001 report. According to it, one of the biggest barriers to demand for mental health care is the stigma associated with mental health conditions. This stigma is universal, pervasive across cultures & countries. It is stifling, and we must do our best to curtail it.

With Mind Matters: An Invitation to Well-Being, we embarked on a mental health campaign in an effort to remove this stigma, by asking people to share their lived experience in order to spread a message of hope & encourage more people to come forward and seek help when needed. Over the last  10 weeks, we have spoken to many such heroes and this is the power of their stories.

Many thanks to @sohilabajaj, @tlllfoundation, @abhinav_bindra & all our wonderful guests.

Over 130 people have been killed & 22 lakh affected as floods ravage Assam once again. Nearly 3 lakh people in Assam are living in relief camps as things stand.

One of the most piercing stories that captured how normal life was upended came from the Cachar Cancer Hospital. With the 150-bed health facility completely inundated, doctors provided chemotherapy to patients outside their hospital on the road. Amid the misery and devastation, doctors and healthcare workers are not losing their spirit and determination to care for their patients.

'The hospital created make-shift rafts to bring in patients,' shares Dr CS Pramesh, Director at Tata Memorial Hospital about the impact of the floods on cancer treatment. Adds that chemotherapy was administered in parking lots & roads when hospital wards were flooded. The ambulance waded through the water-logged areas to ferry staff and patients to & from the hospital.

Providing chemotherapy in floods is a challenge, says Dr Ravi Kannan, Director at Cachar Cancer Research Centre. Hospitals need to be prepared for such floods, he adds.

The duo also talk about the CAR-T trials that have begun in India for cancer treatment. An IIT-Bombay incubated startup Immuno-Act has completed Phase-1 trial of the indigenously produced CAR-T product & are now seeking approvals to start phase 2 & 3 trials.

Phase-1 trial results of CAR-T cell therapy promising, says Dr Pramesh as he opens up about the study. 

I speak with Dr CS Pramesh of Tata Memorial Hospital & Dr Ravi Kannan of Cachar Cancer Research Centre about about the impact of #AssamFloods on cancer treatment, CAR-T trials & more

Be bold & be good, that's what drives us at Nykaa, says Founder & CEO Falguni Nayar and EY Entrepreneur Of The Year.

We have the aspiration & the audacity to go international but we will take baby steps. Golden decade ahead for the beauty & fashion biz in India, she says.

Have been pleasantly surprised at the size & scale Nykaa has reached. The journey has gone far beyond my expectations but along the map I envisaged. 

There are many firsts in our journey. I'm not from IIT, but have built a fantastic tech platform, she tells me. 

Nykaa means let the spotlight of life be on you. Want to tell women to not shy away from being the primary actor of their lives.

On the succession plan she says, 'I'm very much involved in the business, there's a lot to do still. My son and daughter handle a large part of the business, we have professional managers to lead many businesses as well.

I speak with EY Entrepreneur Of The Year, Nykaa Founder & CEO Falguni Nayar about entrepreneurial journey, next big adventure, succession plan & more

I wouldn't like to be an entrepreneur today! The battle for the customer, the access to good talent are much harder today, says @Infosys Chairman Emeritus NR Narayana Murthy.

Still believe in the PSPD model - predictability of revenue, sustainability, focus on profitability & de-risking to run a business. 

'Don't treat an #IPO as just a financing event, it changes everything. You have to honour the trust placed in you,' says Mr Murthy in a message to #startup founders. Adds think of the poorest retail investors before you decide on the IPO.

Also shares a message for #entrepreneurs: #1 No success without difficulties #2 Life will be boring without problems #3 Best time to be an entrepreneur in India 

I speak with Infosys Chairman Emeritus NR Narayana Murthy about lessons in leadership, finding the right successor, merger of new & old culture and learnings from the Late Rahul Bajaj

India's largest airline @indigo.6e is in the eye of a controversy. The company is facing flak after a 90-second video went viral on social media. The airline refused to board a specially abled teenager at the Ranchi Airport & claimed that he was in a state of panic.

IndiGo has responded to the incident calling it unfortunate and truly distressing. However, the airline backed the decision of its staff at the airport saying the teenager was "visibly in a state of panic" and added that "the best possible decision was taken under difficult circumstances."

We deeply regret what has happened but we have to err on the side of safety, says IndiGo CEO Ronojoy Dutta. We will do an internal case study on this and assess what could be done differently.

Fully support my staff in decisions that they make, says IndiGo CEO. Have submitted our response to the regulator the DGCA, it has assured us a quick response over the next few days.

Also added that the airline is in touch with the customer, would like to assure the family of all possible support. Take this as a to-do list, will talk associations working in the area of special needs & get feedback.

'There is a little more training & understanding that everybody needs to go through,' says Shanti Raghavan, Founder of Enable India. Have escalation mechanisms, helplines etc to handle a situation better. Adds CEOs need to give time for understanding the best practices to handle specially-abled passengers. 

Don't think airlines take decision on basis of empathy, have to change the mindset, says Mugdha Kalra, Co-Founder of Not That Different. We need more airports that are designed for inclusion, companies should take feedback from parents of differently abled to see what can be done to improve the experience.

I speak with IndiGo CEO Ronojoy Dutta, Shanti Raghavan - Founder of Enable India & Mugdha Kalra, Co-Founder of Not That Different about how we can make our public spaces & contact-based services sector more inclusive.

As 'Mental Health Awareness Month' begins, we spell out some of the barriers parents face when seeking out the right help for their children in this week's 'Mind Matters: An Invitation To Well-Being'.

'There is a myth that mental health concerns settle with age; but actually half of mental health concerns start before the age of 14,' says Psychotherapist Dr Trinjhna Khattar. She also speaks about some of the behavioural traits that parents can look out for in adolescents that require seeking medical professional help.

“People don’t work in the public sector - TOTAL MYTH!”

A trailblazer, whose name literally means unstoppable, Arundhati Bhattacharya has had an extraordinary journey from growing up in Bokaro to leading India’s largest bank, State Bank of India as its first woman Chairperson and starting afresh in the private sector at 64! 

Arundhati Bhattacharya believes, ‘women need to feel fulfilled, and not do something if they see it as a sacrifice’.

5 years on as the Chairperson of Salesforce India, she tells me she is eager to learn more!

Recently awarded one of India’s highest civilian honours The Padma Shri Arundhati Bhattacharya joins me on YT reloaded to talk about future of banking, the impact agentic AI, life and leadership and busting some myths about the public sector!

Catch her journey, her challenges, and her many triumphs!
